    <text>
        <body>
            <head>56. Paper Prepared in the Bureau of Intelligence and Research, <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of State</orgName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d56fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Country File, Box 3, Algeria:
                    1/77–11/80. Confidential. Carter initialed the paper and wrote “good” in the
                    upper right-hand corner.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-04-05"
                        >April 5, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p rendition="simple_centre">
                <gloss target="#t_INR_1">INR</gloss> AFTERNOON ANALYSIS</p>
            <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName>.]</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">ALGERIA SEEKS BETTER <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">RELATIONS</rs> WITH THE <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                    >US</gloss>
            </p>
            <p>The <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName> regime has important
                economic and political reasons for its current efforts to improve <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> with the
                    <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>. Better <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> would be economically beneficial for
                both sides and would possibly encourage a less confrontational <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> attitude on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recIbrcpzBZ7F4U0S">North-South</rs> and Middle Eastern issues, though
                we would not expect major modifications in <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName>’s anti-imperialist ideology.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d56fn2">An unknown hand highlighted this paragraph.</note>
            </p>
            <p>The <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> leadership feels that
                substantial benefits can be gained by closer <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> with the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                    >US</gloss>:</p>
            <p>—Economic: The paramount goal of the <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                    >Boumediene</persName> regime is the implementation of its ambitious development
                plans. It is urgently seeking decisions from the <orgName
                    corresp="recYVyL4L9y1q41Mt">Federal Power Commission</orgName>
                <note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d56fn3">The U.S. <orgName
                        corresp="recYVyL4L9y1q41Mt">Federal Power Commission</orgName>, established
                    in 1930, regulated interstate electric utilities and the <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz">natural gas</rs> industry.</note> on long-term
                    <gloss target="#t_LNG_1">
                    <rs corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz" type="topic">LNG</rs>
                </gloss> sales, which are needed to finance these plans. <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> also wants additional <orgName
                    corresp="reclzjV0td1de35mW">Exim</orgName> Bank loans and access to <gloss
                    target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> technology.</p>
            <p>—Regional: <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName> hopes to
                dissuade us from our alleged “tilt” toward <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> on the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western
                    Sahara</placeName> issue. At a minimum, <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName> wants continued <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                neutrality and encouragement of Moroccan restraint. <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> requests to purchase limited
                amounts of <rs type="topic" corresp="recJ9z9SORjaCLZG1">military equipment</rs>
                (jeeps, radios, radar) in the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> are intended to
                test our even-handedness and to send signals to <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> that we would not stand behind
                it if it attacked <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>.</p>
            <p>—Global: Closer <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG"
                    >relations</rs> would demonstrate <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName>’s nonalignment and provide proof of <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                    >US</gloss> respect for <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algeria</placeName>’s international status. Algerians also seem to think that
                the <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>
                <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">Administration</rs> will be flexible on
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recIbrcpzBZ7F4U0S">North-South</rs> issues and that a
                dialogue with the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> on this subject would be
                productive.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>’s proven reserves of <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz">natural gas</rs> are the world’s fourth
                largest. It needs long-term cooperation with major gas consumers. <pb facs="0173"
                    n="152" xml:id="pg_152"/> Better <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs> with the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                    >US</gloss> would be likely to lead to a stable economic relationship, resulting
                in sizable commercial contracts for <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> firms (sales
                average about $500 million annually, with prospects for significant increase).</p>
            <p>The specific indications of changing <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd"
                    >Algerian</placeName> attitudes toward the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                include:</p>
            <p>—unusually warm congratulatory messages to President <persName
                    corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> and Secretary <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Vance</persName> in January;<note n="4" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d56fn4">In telegram 32758 to Algiers, February 13, the Department
                    transmitted the text of <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                        >Boumediene</persName>’s message to <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8"
                        >Carter</persName>. (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                    D770051–0589) In telegram 205 from Algiers, January 24, the Embassy transmitted
                    the congratulatory message from <persName corresp="recZPQuJcpaVQkUHt"
                        >Bouteflika</persName> to <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                        >Vance</persName>. (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                    D770025–0102)</note>
            </p>
            <p>—the appointment of an <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                Ambassador to Washington (a confidant of <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                    >Boumediene</persName>) after a two-year delay following the reestablishment of
                    <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>-<gloss
                    target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG">relations</rs>;<note n="5"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d56fn5">Abdelaziz Maoui presented his credentials on June
                    24. <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> severed
                    diplomatic <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="rec0AmVCLv3pyyhNG"
                        >relations</rs> with the United States in June 1967 in response to U.S.
                    assistance to <placeName corresp="recNKHYPMvpKfrRYC">Israel</placeName> during
                    the <rs type="event" corresp="recrQBP5NMrhU9me1">Arab-Israeli War</rs>. The
                    Embassy in Algiers was re-opened in November 1974.</note> and</p>
            <p>—the diversion of several tankers of liquified <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz">natural gas</rs> (<gloss target="#t_LNG_1">
                    <rs corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz" type="topic">LNG</rs>
                </gloss>) to the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> this past winter.<note n="6"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d56fn6">In telegram 337 from Algiers, February 7, the
                    Embassy reported on a press announcement regarding “two special sales contracts
                    of <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName>
                    <gloss target="#t_LNG_1">
                        <rs corresp="recUTvEEyP3EpE7Vz" type="topic">LNG</rs>
                    </gloss> for immediate delivery to <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>.”
                    (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D770043–0307)</note>
            </p>
        </body>
